    {
      "id": "1146092221923964",
      "score": 5,
      "review_title": "Gas N Cars on Meta Quest 3S is exactly t",
      "review_description": "The game basically lets you experience the everyday life of a German gas station worker during current fuel prices — and honestly, that already sounds like a horror game by itself. Customers complain, prices are ridiculous, people get on your nerves, and instead of just smiling politely like in real life, the game lets you finally release that frustration in the most absurd and over-the-top way possible.\n\nWhat makes the game fun is the mix of gas station simulator, chaos, dark humor, and pure VR nonsense. You can serve customers, deal with cars, sell fuel, and then everything can escalate completely. Annoying customers? The game lets you fight back. Someone wants to argue about prices? Well, welcome to the VR gas station experience. Electric car drivers showing up at a gas station? Let’s just say the game has a very questionable but hilarious sense of humor.\n\nOf course, the whole thing is not meant to be taken seriously. It is not realistic, it is not politically correct, and that is exactly why it is funny. It feels like one of those games where the main goal is not to be perfect, but to create stupid, chaotic, funny moments that you can laugh about afterwards.\n\nOn the Meta Quest 3S, the game works really well for this type of experience. The VR controls make the interactions feel much more direct and ridiculous. Filling up cars, handling objects, dealing with customers, and causing complete chaos feels way funnier in VR than it would on a normal screen. The immersion makes the absurd situations even better.\n\nIs it a deep, serious simulator? No.\nIs it realistic? Absolutely not.\nIs it stupid in the best possible way? Yes.\nDid I have fun? Definitely.\n\nIf you like weird VR games, chaotic simulator games, dark humor, and games where you can just mess around without taking anything too seriously, then Gas N Cars is absolutely worth trying.\n\nWould I recommend it? Yes.\nEspecially if you ever wondered what it feels like to work at a gas station in Germany while fuel prices are insane and every customer somehow makes your day worse.",
      "date": 1781910158,
      "review_helpful_count": 0,
      "author_display_name": "Blaulichtfotografie_Bc",
      "author_alias": "Blaulichtfotografie_Bc",
      "developer_response": null
